03787nam a22005535i 9780822377535DE-B159720200915044058.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200915t20132013ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223775357 a10.1515/97808223775352doi  a(DE-B1597)553668  a(OCoLC)855897557  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aPN1993.5.J3bF859 2013 7aPER0040302bisacsh04a791.4309522231 aFuruhata, Yuriko, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCinema of Actuality :bJapanese Avant-Garde Filmmaking in the Season of Image Politics /cYuriko Furuhata. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (280 p.) :b29 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAsia-Pacific: Culture, Politics, and Society00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tOne. Intermedial Experiments and the Rise of the Eizō Discourse -- tTwo. Cinema, Event, and Artifactuality -- tThree. Remediating Journalism: Politics and the Media Event -- tFour. Diagramming the Landscape: Power and the Fūkeiron Discourse -- tFive. Hijacking Television: News and Militant Cinema -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDuring the 1960s and early 1970s, Japanese avant-garde filmmakers intensely explored the shifting role of the image in political activism and media events. Known as the "season of politics," the era was filled with widely covered dramatic events from hijackings and hostage crises to student protests. This season of politics was, Yuriko Furuhata argues, the season of image politics. Well-known directors, including Oshima Nagisa, Matsumoto Toshio, Wakamatsu Kōji, and Adachi Masao, appropriated the sensationalized media coverage of current events, turning news stories into material for timely critique and intermedial experimentation. Cinema of Actuality analyzes Japanese avant-garde filmmakers' struggle to radicalize cinema in light of the intensifying politics of spectacle and a rapidly changing media environment, one that was increasingly dominated by television. Furuhata demonstrates how avant-garde filmmaking intersected with media history, and how sophisticated debates about film theory emerged out of dialogues with photography, television, and other visual arts.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aMotion picturesxPolitical aspectszJapanxHistoryy20th century. 0aMotion pictureszJapanxHistoryy20th century. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822377535zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822377535423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822377535.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles